instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "The controller, also running on the Raspberry Pi, subscribes to the RabbitMQ broker for control messages that indicate whether to turn the heatbed or fan on or off. Upon receiving a command, the controller forwards it to the low‑level driver, which writes the command to the GPIO pins via MOSFETs and optocouplers to actuate the heatbed and fan. The low‑level driver incorporates a safe protocol to ensure that conflicting commands are not issued simultaneously, but the documents do not specify any authentication or confirmation mechanisms beyond the driver’s internal safety checks."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "No explicit synchronization frequencies, latency requirements, or temporal granularity are specified in the documents. The low‑level driver is described as periodically reading temperature data and checking for commands, but the sampling period or message latency is not quantified."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin is orchestrated around a message‑oriented middleware (RabbitMQ, AMQP). The Raspberry Pi hosts the controller (bang‑bang logic) and the low‑level driver (sensor I/O and command handling). The controller consumes temperature measurements and publishes control commands for the fan and heatbed; the low‑level driver publishes sensor data and consumes control commands. The system follows a publish‑subscribe pattern with the RabbitMQ broker as the central coordinator. Resource management is handled by the Raspberry Pi’s GPIO, MOSFETs, and optocouplers for current isolation. The overall architecture is a centralized, broker‑based coordination pattern with real‑time data flow between physical and digital layers."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The incubator DT lifecycle comprises: (1) Physical Twin (PT) design and construction (insulated box, heatbed, fan, Raspberry Pi, DS18S20 sensors, PCB with MOSFETs and optocouplers); (2) Model development – two thermal models (Model A with 2 free parameters, Model B with 4 free parameters) to predict internal temperature; (3) Calibration – on‑demand calibration using collected sensor data to update Model B parameters; (4) Deployment – real‑time data ingestion via RabbitMQ, controller and low‑level driver communication; (5) Monitoring – real‑time visualization, anomaly detection via Kalman filter, heatbed state estimation; (6) Adaptation – self‑adaptation loop that schedules experiments, re‑calibrates Model B, re‑configures Kalman filter and controller; (7) Evolution – iterative refinement of models and control logic based on new experiments and what‑if simulations."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model parameters are calibrated using a dedicated experiment that records temperature trajectories.  For Model A: C_air = 616.56 J/K, G_box = 0.65 J/K.  For Model B: C_air = 486.12 J/K, G_box = 0.856 J/K, C_heater = 33.65 J/K, G_heater = 0.87 J/K.  Validation is performed by comparing simulated temperature curves against experimental data; Model B shows a reduced maximum discrepancy (6 °C vs 7 °C).  Anomaly detection and heatbed state estimation are achieved with a Kalman filter that fuses measured temperatures with Model B predictions.  The Kalman filter also serves as an error‑detection mechanism, flagging deviations that trigger safety actions.  Safety constraints are enforced by the low‑level driver’s safe protocol, which limits fan voltage and heatbed duty cycle.  Quality assurance is implicit in the calibration/validation loop and the continuous monitoring of model performance via the DT framework."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "All communication between the controller, low‑level driver, and the physical sensors/actuators is mediated by a single RabbitMQ broker that runs locally on the Raspberry Pi. RabbitMQ implements the AMQP protocol over TCP/IP. The network topology is a single‑node broker with the controller and driver as clients on the same device; no external network links are described. The documents do not provide explicit bandwidth, latency, reliability, redundancy, or security requirements for this local communication."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The digital twin components (controller, low‑level driver, and RabbitMQ broker) are deployed on a Raspberry Pi 4 Model B, an edge device that runs the system on‑premise. The documents do not detail computational or storage requirements, scalability, or availability mechanisms beyond the fact that the system is hosted on the Pi. No cloud or multi‑node deployment is described."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "Integration with external systems is achieved via RabbitMQ (AMQP) for inter‑component communication. Sensor data and control states are published to a time‑series database (implied) and visualised on a dashboard. The integration pattern is publish‑subscribe; the DT components act as both publishers and subscribers. No explicit interoperability standards beyond AMQP are mentioned, and the system can be extended to integrate with other enterprise systems or DTs through the same broker or via REST/HTTP endpoints (not detailed in the documents)."
]

instance security_and_safety_considerations : DTDFVocab:SecuritySafety [
    base:desc "The low‑level driver incorporates a safe protocol to keep the device in a safe state during operation. Communication between the controller, low‑level driver, and the physical twin is performed via RabbitMQ, an open‑source message broker. No explicit cybersecurity protocols, access control mechanisms, authentication systems, or threat mitigation strategies are described in the documents."
]